Football Performance and Economic Dynamics Across the Top Five European Leagues

Introduction to Coding and Data Management part 2 - Matteo Fozzato

Introduction: Modern Football's Landscape

In recent years, football has experienced a remarkable transformation, both on and off the pitch, particularly in Europe’s top five leagues: the English Premier League (EPL), La Liga (Spain), Serie A (Italy), Bundesliga (Germany), and Ligue 1 (France). These leagues have not only captured global attention due to the quality of play and star-studded teams but have also become economic powerhouses, driving significant revenue through broadcasting rights, sponsorships, and merchandising.

The Premier League, for instance, has consistently led the way in revenue generation, largely due to lucrative television deals and its broad international fan base. Meanwhile, La Liga has showcased its unique brand of football, highlighted by the success of clubs like FC Barcelona and Real Madrid, which have global appeal. Serie A, after a period of decline, has seen a resurgence with increased investment and the return of top-tier talent. The Bundesliga, known for its fan-friendly policies and financial prudence, continues to produce competitive teams and nurturing young talent. Ligue 1, although traditionally seen as a feeder league, has gained prominence with clubs like Paris Saint-Germain making substantial investments to bring in world-class players.

However, these leagues also face challenges, including financial disparities among clubs, the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on matchday revenues, and the growing influence of wealthy owners. As football continues to globalize, these top leagues strive to balance sporting excellence with sustainable economic models, ensuring the long-term health of the sport.

Research purpose

  • Analyzing the performance on the pitch of clubs (and whole leagues) across Europe's top 5 leagues
  • Analyizing the financial situation across the top 5 leagues
  • Analyzing the correlation between sport performance and economic parameters
  • Getting insights about players, both about performance and finances

All of the steps of the notebook will be oriented towards fulfilling these pruposes.

Project overview

The project will be divided in four parts:

  • Part 1: Installing and importing necessary libraries

  • Part 2: Data cleaning

  • Part 3: Data combining and reshaping

  • Part 4: Data analisys and visualization

Datasets

  • club.csv: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/sanjeetsinghnaik/football-club-market-value-2021
  • raw_wages1.csv: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/ultimus/football-salaries-dataset?select=raw_wages.csv
  • players.csv: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/sanjeetsinghnaik/most-expensive-footballers-2021
  • UCL_AllTime_Performance_Table.csv: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/fardifaalam170041060/champions-league-dataset-1955-2023

These are the four datasets which will be used throughout the notebook.

There are a few problems with the column 'Last Trans. Fee'. It has many string parts and the numbers are inidcated with M (millions) or K(thousands); I will need to keep only numbers and convert them based on the letter they are followed by.

In [251]:
# Function to convert fee values
def convert_fee(fee):
    if pd.isna(fee):  # Check for NaN or None values
        return np.nan
    if isinstance(fee, str):
        # Remove any surrounding whitespace and currency symbols
        fee = fee.strip().replace('€', '')
        
        # Use regex to find the numerical part and the letter
        match = re.match(r'(\d+\.?\d*)([MK]?)', fee)
        if match:
            number, unit = match.groups()
            number = float(number) if number else 0
            if unit == 'M':
                return number * 1_000_000
            elif unit == 'K':
                return number * 1_000
            else:
                return number
    return np.nan

# Apply the conversion function to the "Last Trans. Fee" column
wages_filtered['Last Trans. Fee'] = wages_filtered['Last Trans. Fee'].apply(convert_fee)

# Check the updated column
print(wages_filtered[['Last Trans. Fee']])

def get_competition_name(club):
    for league, clubs in league_clubs.items():
        if club in clubs:
            return league
    return None

Market Value vs. Performance

In [281]:
# Market Value vs. Performance (Points)
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.scatterplot(x='Market Value Of Club In Millions(€)', y='Points', hue='Competition Name', data=football, s=100)
plt.title('Market Value vs Points Across Leagues')
plt.xlabel('Market Value Of Club In Millions(€)')
plt.ylabel('Points')
plt.show()

There is no clear correlation between market value and points across the leagues. This suggests that spending more on players does not necessarily guarantee success in terms of points. The distribution of data points for each league varies. The Premier League has the most teams clustered towards higher market values and points, indicating a potential correlation within that league. However, this trend is not consistent across all leagues. There are outliers, such as the team with the highest market value but relatively low points. These outliers suggest that other factors beyond market value, such as team chemistry, tactics, and individual player performance, can influence a team's success.

The introduction of financial fair play regulations in European football has aimed to limit excessive spending on players. This may have contributed to a less pronounced correlation between market value and points. The quality of a team's manager and their ability to assemble a cohesive squad can have a significant impact on performance, regardless of market value.

Also we need to keep in mind that the points result also from the history of the teams, not just recent results. This tells us that Premier League has both good history and a good financial health in the present.

The Premier League has the youngest average age, while LaLiga has the oldest. Bundesliga, Ligue 1, and Serie A have similar average ages. There seems to be a weak negative correlation between squad size and average age. Leagues with larger squad sizes tend to have slightly younger average ages, while leagues with smaller squad sizes have slightly older average ages.

Different leagues may have varying philosophies regarding squad size and player development. Some leagues may prioritize developing young talent, leading to larger squads with younger average ages. The level of competition within a league can also impact squad size and age. Leagues with higher levels of competition may require larger squads to cope with injuries and fixture congestion.

There is no clear correlation between average market value and average age across the leagues. This suggests that teams with higher average market values do not necessarily have older or younger players. This is because market value depends on age, but not necessarily in a linear way. Some players might reach their peak strength around 27 or 28 years old, so their market value might be high, but younger players with potential have also a high market value, despite still not being in their best form. The squad and league composition might vary, so for example Premier League, which is also a more physical demanding league, needs experienced and strong players, who are older. Bundesliga and Ligue 1 have a less physical game, giving young players the opportunity to show off.

Conclusions

The findings of this notebook perfectly match the initial research purposes. The main findings will be explained below.

The analysis of football clubs and leagues reveals that financial investment does not necessarily equate to success on the field. While the Premier League consistently shows a positive correlation between market value and on-field performance, this trend is not uniformly observed across other major European leagues. Factors such as team chemistry, tactical approaches, and managerial expertise significantly impact a team's success, suggesting that football remains unpredictable and complex despite financial disparities. The weak correlation between market value, goals, assists, and points highlights that high spending does not guarantee top performance, reflecting the impact of strategic planning and individual talent.

The study also highlights variations in league dynamics, with the Premier League leading in financial metrics such as market value and salaries. This is attributed to its substantial television revenue and global appeal. However, leagues like LaLiga and Serie A exhibit competitive balance and historical success, proving that wealth isn't the sole determinant of victory. Factors such as squad size, age, and salary distribution also influence league and team characteristics, with younger and larger squads often correlating with higher performance levels.

Furthermore, the geographical distribution of high-value players underscores the dominance of European and South American countries, bolstered by strong domestic leagues and youth development programs. While financial powerhouses like the Premier League have an advantage, this analysis reinforces that success in football is multifaceted, relying on a combination of financial investment, tactical insight, and the development of talent.
